    <h1>UPS &amp; DOWNS</h1>
    <h2>Hong Kong Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent and South Korea Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent trace how both places saw a spike in Covid-19 cases de&#xAD;spite ini&#xAD;tial suc&#xAD;cess in curb&#xAD;ing the out&#xAD;break</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200730/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-30"><time>2020-07-30</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline">Jan 20: Feb 4: Feb 18: Feb 20: Feb 21: Feb 23: Feb 26: Feb 27: Feb 29: March 3:&#xD;&#xA;March 22: April 3: May 6: So&#xAD;cial dis&#xAD;tanc&#xAD;ing eased, as daily new cases plunge to sin&#xAD;gle dig&#xAD;its. May 11: May 20: May 26: May 29: June 28: &#x2022; &#x2022; &#x2022; changmc@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>SOUTH KOREA</p>
    <p>South Korea re­ports first case – a 35-year-old Chi­nese wo­man liv­ing in north-western city In­cheon who had vis­ited Wuhan.</p>
    <p>All ar­rivals from Hubei prov­ince, epi­cen­tre of the out­break in China, banned.</p>
    <p>Pa­tient 31, a 61-year-old wo­man and mem­ber of the se­cre­tive church Shin­cheonji, tests pos­i­tive in south-eastern city Daegu.</p>
    <p>First death de­tected – a 63-year-old man who tests pos­i­tive posthu­mously – as num­ber of cases, many traced back to Pa­tient 31, starts spik­ing.</p>
    <p>Daegu and neigh­bour­ing Cheongdo des­ig­nated “spe­cial care zones” to al­low more funds and re­sources to be di­verted to those places to fight the virus.</p>
    <p>Virus alert level raised to red, the high­est level, as num­ber of cases spike to 604. New spring term for schools pushed from March 2 to March 9. They will even­tu­ally re­open on April 8 with on­line lessons.</p>
    <p>First drive-through test­ing cen­tre opens, al­low­ing test­ing to be done in 10 min­utes.</p>
    <p>Daily fig­ure of 505 new cases out­paces China (450) for the first time. Its total tally hits 1,766.</p>
    <p>Num­ber of daily new cases soars to a record high of 909, as test­ing of all Shin­cheonji’s 200,000 mem­bers be­gins.</p>
    <p>Pres­i­dent Moon Jae-in de­clares “war” against virus, puts all gov­ern­ment agen­cies on 24-hour alert.</p>
    <p>Strict so­cial dis­tanc­ing mea­sures im­posed. 10,000 thresh­old is crossed with 10,062 cases recorded. How­ever, num­ber of new cases drops be­low 100 and will con­tinue to fall in the months ahead.</p>
    <p>MEA­SURES EASED CASES START RIS­ING</p>
    <p>New clus­ter linked to Seoul’s nightlife district Itae­won hits 94 cases, trig­ger­ing fears of se­cond wave. Schools re­sume phys­i­cal lessons in phases, start­ing with high school se­niors.</p>
    <p>Mask-wear­ing now manda­tory on all forms of pub­lic trans­port.</p>
    <p>Strict so­cial dis­tanc­ing re-en­forced in Seoul and neigh­bour­ing Gyeonggi prov­ince and In­cheon city. Gov­ern­ment an­nounces three-level so­cial dis­tanc­ing pol­icy</p>
    <p>Cur­rent state of Level 1 (be­low 50 new cases a day): No spe­cific re­stric­tions.</p>
    <p>Level 2 (daily new cases rise to 51 to 100):</p>
    <p>In­door meet­ings of more than 50 peo­ple and out­door gath­er­ings of more than 100 banned.</p>
    <p>Level 3 (daily new cases ex­ceed 100): School clo­sures, ban on gath­er­ings of 10 or more peo­ple.</p>

